# Python Rules
The following rules ALWAYS apply when working with python code.

## Code Style
- use `p_<path_name>` syntax for `Path` objects
- use single quotes for strings whenever possible, except for docstrings
- Variable names should match class names in snake_case: `my_class = MyClass()`, not `obj = MyClass()`
- if you're writing code in a working file (anything in /notebooks) code can be more "rough" - don't worry about docstrings. this is code to be tested out in an interactive interpreter. don't create new notebook files.

## Dates and calendars
- Do not construct `date(...)`, `datetime(...)`, or `time(...)` with raw calendar literals **inside function bodies** unless the user **explicitly** asks for that pattern—use **module-level** named constants, parameters, or config-driven values and reference those names in logic.
- At **module** scope, avoid repeating the same raw `date` / `datetime` / `time` literals in many places; centralize scenario dates in named constants (typically after imports) so one assignment defines the scenario.

## Code Structure
- ALWAYS ensure your code is clean and DRY
- **NEVER put imports inside functions/methods** - ALL imports go at the top of the file. The ONLY exception is circular import avoidance with TYPE_CHECKING blocks.
- Put all imports on their own line, always use absolute imports
- Never use `__all__` - always import from explicit paths (e.g., `from pkg.module import Thing` not re-exports)
- If function arguments are long (>3 args), left-indent with each arg on its own line
- Keep code readable with blank lines between logical sections (before/after returns, after loops/conditionals)
- Don't overuse try/except - sometimes it's okay for code to fail and propagate errors
- never export things in an `__ini__.py` file, just import them directly where needed.

## File Structure
- Define functions above where they're called so code reads top-to-bottom
- Prefer fewer classes per file when appropriate
- avoid generic names like `base.py`. Eg for a class `MyBase` call the file `my_base.py`

## Type Annotations
- Use modern syntax: `list[T]`, `dict[K, V]`, `X | None` (not `Optional[X]`, not `List[Dict]`)
- Annotate empty collections explicitly: `items: list[str] = []`, not bare `items = []`; use typed `default_factory` helpers for dataclass fields, not bare `list`/`dict`
- Use `**kw` instead of `**kwargs`
- Don't use `Any` unless absolutely necessary
- Never use `from __future__ import annotations`
- use `@override` if a method is overriding its superclass' function
- if type errors happen in multiple places, attempt to fix them in a generic base class so they can be fixed/ignored in a single place only.

## Comments & Documentation
- Be concise: "Thing to do" not "The thing to do"
- Comments should describe the code, not reference the conversation
- Use numpy style docstrings

## Pandas
- Name dataframes `df_<name>` not `<name>_df`
- Access columns with dot notation: `df.my_col` not `df['my_col']`
- Use method chaining with `\`, new functions on their own line
- Create new columns with `.assign`

## Linting & Type Checking
After completing changes, run linting and type checking:
```bash
make lint                              # ruff check + format check
make format                            # auto-format with ruff
uv run pyright src tests               # type check
```

- Both ERRORS and WARNINGS must ALWAYS be fixed. no exceptions. ever.
- Fix type issues by correcting types, adding annotations, or restructuring code. Don't remove existing `# ty: ignore` comments unless fixing the underlying issue.
- You must fix type errors in files you modify, even if unrelated to your main task.

## Running Python
- Use `uv run --frozen python -m <module>` to run scripts

## General
- NEVER create markdown summaries unless explicitly requested

## SQLAlchemy & Alembic
- ORM models live in `src/vessel_valuation/db/models.py`; keep them declarative and table-focused.
- Use `db/repository.py` for session management and queries — callbacks and engine code receive domain objects, not ORM instances.
- When adding or changing columns: update the ORM model, create an Alembic revision under `db/migrations/`, review autogenerated SQL, then run migrations locally before relying on the new schema in code.
- Tests use SQLite in-memory — repository code must remain backend-agnostic (no Postgres-only SQL outside migrations).

## Dash
- Callbacks belong in `app/callbacks.py` (or view-specific callback modules). Keep them thin: parse inputs, call `validation` / `model` / `repository`, return layout props.
- Do not import SQLAlchemy or valuation formulas directly in layout modules.
- Shared UI state and IDs live in layout/view modules; business rules stay in `src/vessel_valuation/`.

